  "prompt": "Why does the RBI increase the repo rate during inflation and decrease it during deflation?",
  "response": "The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) adjusts the repo rate as part of its monetary policy to manage the economy. The repo rate is the rate at which commercial banks borrow money from the RBI. Changes in this rate influence borrowing costs, consumer spending, and investment.\n\nHere\u2019s why the RBI changes the repo rate during inflation and deflation:\n\n1. **During Inflation**:\n   - **Objective**: To control inflation, which is characterized by a general increase in prices and decrease in the purchasing power of money.\n   - **Action**: RBI increases the repo rate.\n   - **Reasoning**: Higher repo rates make borrowing more expensive for commercial banks. Consequently, this leads to higher interest rates for loans to consumers and businesses. Higher borrowing costs generally reduce spending and investment, slowing down economic activity. This helps reduce demand-pull inflation, where demand for goods and services exceeds supply.\n\n2. **During Deflation**:\n   - **Objective**: To combat deflation, which involves a general decrease in price levels and economic activity.\n   - **Action**: RBI decreases the repo rate.\n   - **Reasoning**: Lower repo rates make borrowing cheaper for commercial banks. This encourages banks to lend more to consumers and businesses at lower interest rates. Increased borrowing and spending stimulate economic activity and demand for goods and services. This can help counteract deflation by encouraging consumption and investment.\n\nIn summary, during inflation, the RBI raises the repo rate to make borrowing costlier, thereby reducing spending and cooling down the overheated economy. During deflation, it lowers the repo rate to make borrowing cheaper, encouraging spending and investment to stimulate the economy.",
